recordings.loc: Caduaño, Baja California Sur
recordings.rmk: same bird as prior recording; singing while foraging 1-4 m up under the crown of a short mesquite tree in natural vegetation; very soft song at close range;  seems to be regular vocal appropriation right from the start, e.g. of Hooded Oriole, Ash-throated Flycatcher (after 6:43), and a great House Finch after 11:00 (unless it was a real one?); no other gnatcatcher in view; male showing some alternate plumage in black brow; started scolding at end, perhaps at me, although I had been at close range in plain sight the whole time; annotation said "almost no other bird species vocalizing", noting only Ladder-backed Woodpecker and Orange-crowned Warbler, to which I added Verdin while reviewing it; recording gets  better with time, especially after 4:30; interval shortened at 7:28 by 38 seconds to remove partial annotation; 2nd of two recordings;

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Bird foraging alone in the lower branches of a walnut tree initially 5m above the ground, moving steadily to the north at roughly the same height. Foraging by hopping along the branch and between branches, picking at leaves along the way. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Grizzly Flats Road, Angeles National Forest, Los Angeles County, California
recordings.rmk:
This was a family of blue-gray gnatcatchers.  I saw begging behavior consisting of rapid wing flapping by perched birds directed toward an adult.  The fledglings could fly and they were following the adult.  There were four birds and at least two were fledglings (based on their behavior).  

Seen well.  Not photographed.

Recorded with an Olympus LS-10 equipped with a Sennheiser MKE-400 short shotgun microphone.  I cropped the original file.

Recorded about 0.75 miles up the Grizzly Flats Road from the Angeles Crest Highway in an area that burned extensively during the Station Fire in 2009.  Chaparral in this area is recovering rapidly.

In North America, Aphelocoma californica is known as the Western Scrub-Jay, not the California Scrub-Jay.  It would be helpful if Xeno-Canto would adopt names for species established by the AOU and in widespread use in this hemisphere.

recordings.loc: Lewis & Clark Caverns State Park, MT
recordings.rmk: Heard it call, this is a rare species for the location and this is mostly for record purposes. It responded vigorously to playback and seemed like it was on territory. I had great views of it; a male with clear eye ring, black on front of head, and long black tail with outer feathers. Even though it is out of range, the habitat is very much what they use throughout the southern areas in the western US. (displaced Great Basin type scrub/juniper).
